23:24.880 --> 23:35.170
So an auction house really is not a good source to... Well, if Max pays a million dollars for a book, you know, it's going to Getty.

23:35.390 --> 23:37.092
Okay, but, you know, but Getty's not a collector.

23:37.933 --> 23:40.896
You know, Getty's an institution now.

23:41.316 --> 23:44.179
I don't think he's buying it.

23:44.920 --> 23:47.042
Just bought the Ptolemy for a month and a half.

23:47.082 --> 23:47.963
Okay, I don't know.

23:49.259 --> 23:50.842
So you don't know.

23:50.962 --> 23:51.683
I don't know.

23:52.264 --> 23:53.886
Listen, Corp buys a lot from us.

23:53.946 --> 23:56.671
And I don't know and I don't care who they buy from.

23:56.771 --> 23:58.053
I just want to keep buying.

23:58.333 --> 23:59.636
We have about five minutes, I guess.

24:02.801 --> 24:06.386
You just said there's something always there, something there for everyone.

24:06.406 --> 24:06.927
Absolutely.

24:08.029 --> 24:09.892
That was an inch of my talk last night.

24:09.912 --> 24:14.599
Anybody who wants to collect books, in almost every sale, you can find something, whether it's early.

24:14.619 --> 24:16.903
Because book collecting takes so many different forms.

24:17.423 --> 24:27.035
You can collect by subject, you can collect by era, you can collect by illustrator, you can collect by author, you can collect by number of pages, you can collect by color of binding.

24:27.235 --> 24:34.064
I could take you to any bookstore anywhere and I can show you something that would turn you on, no matter what you're interested in.

24:34.925 --> 24:38.349
So in that sense, it's a very democratic pursuit.

24:38.549 --> 24:39.010
Absolutely.

24:39.479 --> 24:45.545
You can do it for almost no money at all.

24:45.605 --> 24:47.427
You can choose to define your collection.

24:47.627 --> 24:50.170
And you don't exclude that kind of person from your halls.

24:50.970 --> 24:53.713
Well, in a way you'd exclude them.

24:54.113 --> 24:59.439
Well, you can come in here and buy things for paying 50 bucks.

25:00.440 --> 25:01.681
Yes, you can.

25:01.841 --> 25:02.502
Yes, you can.

25:02.682 --> 25:06.786
I'll tell you, I'm kicking my ass right now because I had a number last time and I didn't

25:07.458 --> 25:14.207
I now find a book that's found really, sorry, it's called Cookery Books by Pennell's wife, Elizabeth Pennell.

25:14.347 --> 25:14.908
Elizabeth Pennell.

25:14.988 --> 25:16.210
I think they went for $350.

25:16.770 --> 25:18.232
That's a pretty good price for that book.

25:18.453 --> 25:21.737
But what I'm trying to say is, you know, I'm sorry I didn't buy that.

25:21.857 --> 25:25.522
I mean, because I love what's holding up with my illustrated books.

25:25.542 --> 25:31.470
You know, we don't, anybody who's interested in collecting, whether it's books or anything else, is welcome in an auction house.

25:31.490 --> 25:32.732
Do we really have anything for them?

25:33.032 --> 25:33.493
Not really.

25:33.573 --> 25:36.537
I mean, if you're going to be a $50 collector, it's a terrible mistake to

25:36.989 --> 25:38.351
to spend that money in an auction house.

25:38.431 --> 25:39.312
Oh, I agree.

25:39.973 --> 25:52.128
But in terms of... You'd rather deal with the dealers?

25:53.830 --> 25:56.193
You'd rather do business with the dealers?

25:56.213 --> 26:00.839
In the long run, the dealers are more important.

26:00.859 --> 26:02.361
Well, because they're here all the time.

26:02.481 --> 26:05.545
The collector's going to pay more money for the individual item.

26:05.727 --> 26:09.371
Not necessarily true, but generally true.

26:09.391 --> 26:10.152
But you can't figure it out.

26:10.172 --> 26:12.755
Is that going to figure in the market for the dealer?

26:12.795 --> 26:15.098
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

26:15.118 --> 26:17.341
Dealers are bidding on commission for clients.

26:18.142 --> 26:22.427
A lot of what they're buying here and the prices seem to be very high.

26:22.447 --> 26:24.609
A dealer isn't going to put it in his inventory.

26:24.629 --> 26:28.614
The higher the price of a book, the less of a marketer.

26:28.634 --> 26:32.258
A dealer is, don't forget, a dealer is just like an auction house.

26:33.284 --> 26:39.110
The most difficult thing in running an auction house is not finding customers, it's finding material to sell.

26:39.131 --> 26:40.192
And the same is true with dealers.

26:40.632 --> 26:45.478
The light blood of a dealer is not selling, it's acquiring material.

26:45.498 --> 26:50.924
So if a good item comes up for sale, it's absolutely essential.

26:51.164 --> 26:58.492
You talk to any dealer, there are dealers that go from book fair to book fair, they take a booth in a book fair, they couldn't give a shit if they sell anything.

26:58.592 --> 27:02.937
They want to get to the other dealer's booth before anybody else does.

27:03.389 --> 27:08.856
The higher the price of a book, the less of a spread there is between the buying price.

27:08.876 --> 27:13.803
If a dealer buys a book for $50 or $100 or $200, sure, he's buying it at half of what he'll sell it.

27:13.823 --> 27:15.145
The seller will be buying it for stock.

27:15.365 --> 27:16.226
Right.

27:16.247 --> 27:19.651
The higher the price, the greater the likelihood he's buying for a client.

27:20.873 --> 27:22.815
I think that's a rule of thumb that you could apply.

27:22.916 --> 27:24.097
I would apply that, sure.

27:24.117 --> 27:27.542
I can't believe that somebody, I see some small dealers are paying $2,000, $3,000, $4,000 for a book.

27:27.722 --> 27:28.744
They're not putting it in inventory.

27:29.104 --> 27:31.287
If either got a commission and they make a 10% markup,

27:31.520 --> 27:33.743
Or they have a pretty good idea who they're going to sell it to.

27:34.183 --> 27:36.466
And because, look, remember one thing.

27:36.486 --> 27:39.469
The auction price is public knowledge.

27:39.489 --> 27:42.833
You can't buy a $5,000 book and offer it for $12,000.

27:43.093 --> 27:43.934
But a lot of people do.

27:44.455 --> 27:46.037
And some get away with it, some don't.

27:46.337 --> 27:47.679
But there are dealers who will not buy it.

27:47.699 --> 27:51.423
Well, dealers I won't name because I was at all the Bradley Martin sales.

27:51.804 --> 27:54.827
And I saw especially the American Literature sale.

27:55.803 --> 27:58.607
And it was advertised as Bradley Martin's own copy.

27:58.767 --> 28:00.730
Yeah, but did you check the cost?

28:01.331 --> 28:02.773
I kept notes and everything.

28:02.793 --> 28:03.474
I got all the prices.

28:03.574 --> 28:04.455
Oh, but check your cost.

28:04.475 --> 28:12.226
Dealers, I've seen a lot of Bradley Martin stuff in the market now, and it's marked up maybe 25%, maybe 30%, and maybe a little more research as Madonna.

28:12.547 --> 28:14.850
I haven't found things that have been doubled or tripled.

28:14.870 --> 28:16.172
But then again, what's wrong with that?

28:16.432 --> 28:17.534
What, doubling or tripling?

28:18.155 --> 28:18.515
Yeah.

28:18.575 --> 28:20.538
Well, you run the risk of being called a Donut.

28:21.319 --> 28:25.405
That you're, what do you call it, a...

28:25.672 --> 28:29.676
An opportunist or whatever?

28:29.697 --> 28:33.060
Look, there are dealers who will not buy at the auction because then the cost is known.

28:34.302 --> 28:37.665
There's something... If you go into a... Look, it's human nature.

28:37.685 --> 28:47.076
If you go into a store and you buy something, no matter how much you want it, you buy that tie and you spend $60 for a tie, it would really infuriate me if I know that the store paid $15 for that tie.

28:47.276 --> 28:48.658
It's probably what they paid for it.

28:48.678 --> 28:54.004
It may be, but if I really knew it... Now, the market is 100%, and that's why I buy on sale.

28:54.024 --> 28:55.105
The market is only 50%.

28:55.608 --> 28:56.989
But, you know, it's that kind of thing.

28:57.049 --> 29:06.458
People don't want to be told that the dealer has made an enormous profit off him, especially if he's a good customer.

29:07.499 --> 29:09.381
You're my good customer, and I'm a dealer.

29:09.941 --> 29:10.762
I have you in mind.

29:11.222 --> 29:12.884
Listen, I bought this at Bradley Martin.

29:12.904 --> 29:16.467
I had you in mind, and I'll sell it to you at only a 10% markup.

29:16.487 --> 29:17.888
How can you turn it down?

29:17.908 --> 29:22.533
But if I offer it to you a double, and you can read the catalog as well as I can, you'll say, my God, what a crook.

29:23.033 --> 29:25.075
But then there's another whole...

29:25.055 --> 29:29.740
separate psychology, it could also be operating two other ones.

29:29.760 --> 29:44.337
One is, somebody could buy it at Martin, advertise it for a hugely inflated price as a promotional gimmick for themselves to a public who read the words Martin in the newspapers but really doesn't know what the hell was going on, just for name recognition.

29:44.918 --> 29:49.143
And you don't know what the guy sold it for, actually, if he finally unloaded the book.

29:49.163 --> 29:53.408
You can advertise it for anything and make the same percent above view it.

29:54.130 --> 29:58.114
The dealer's prices are very suspect.

29:58.454 --> 30:01.237
I hope you know that.

30:01.317 --> 30:02.638
How do you mean?

30:02.678 --> 30:04.980
Look at dealer's catalogs.

30:05.080 --> 30:08.804
You say, oh, he got $4,000.

30:09.064 --> 30:11.687
No, he's asking $4,000 for that.

30:11.707 --> 30:13.148
10% discount, no sweat.

30:13.168 --> 30:14.429
20% discount sometime.

30:14.609 --> 30:16.831
And a 30% discount occasionally.

30:17.032 --> 30:20.114
Especially if it goes from one catalog to the next.

30:20.154 --> 30:20.855
Well, no.

30:21.035 --> 30:22.176
No, it depends with the buyers.

30:22.817 --> 30:23.918
And there are many people

30:24.353 --> 30:26.336
who in the book business feel that they can't negotiate.

30:27.097 --> 30:27.738
So would a dealer.

30:27.758 --> 30:29.521
You know, a dealer is no different than anybody else.

30:29.541 --> 30:34.528
If I ask for $4,000 for that book, and you're going to pay me $4,000, I'm not going to offer you a discount.

30:34.548 --> 30:38.073
On the other hand, if you ask for a discount, I might grant it to you.

30:38.093 --> 30:41.478
Scheide was that late, Mr. Scheide's father.

30:41.659 --> 30:45.925
I went to all of Rosenbach's correspondence in Philadelphia, and he was a bicker.

30:46.626 --> 30:48.589
I mean, you bought the Google Word Bible for a minute.

30:48.873 --> 30:51.316
And you start to say, well, there's a couple of leaves missing now.

30:51.376 --> 30:53.498
We're just trying to beat them down on the tracks.

30:53.699 --> 30:55.361
No, but that's absolutely invaluable.

30:55.381 --> 30:55.561
Yeah.

30:57.243 --> 30:59.646
I think we've got some good stuff here.

31:00.547 --> 31:17.226
I guess the difference between book selling today, and not necessarily in the auction business, but book dealers, and say on a Rosenbach day, is that guys like Krugs and Rosenbach would buy big ticket items for stock.

31:17.645 --> 31:23.914
And what you just said is when you see a big-ticket item, you can just assume that he's buying that somewhere.

31:24.034 --> 31:26.838
It's hard to generalize.

31:29.062 --> 31:33.368
And I'm not sure that you're right.

31:34.690 --> 31:45.846
My guess is that when Krauss or Rosenbach or the Drakes or anybody else bought big items for stock,

31:47.193 --> 31:49.976
I'll give you a good quote.

31:49.996 --> 31:52.980
You never have too many good quotes.

31:53.000 --> 31:53.441
What the hell?

31:53.461 --> 31:53.981
How does it go?

31:59.889 --> 32:03.112
Something to the effect of, when I buy books, I never make mistakes.

32:03.793 --> 32:05.495
When I make a mistake, it becomes my inventory.

32:07.298 --> 32:16.609
So Rosenbach will buy something with Goheny in mind, or with Flagler in mind, or with Huntington in mind.

32:16.893 --> 32:18.555
And there's Bell Green in mind.

32:19.277 --> 32:20.158
Fine, but they don't buy it.

32:20.859 --> 32:22.421
Lo and behold, it becomes inventory.

32:22.441 --> 32:23.142
So he makes a mistake.

32:23.302 --> 32:24.204
Now, there are cases.

32:24.885 --> 32:28.310
Hey, Krauss clearly bought a Gutenberg for publicity.

32:28.891 --> 32:30.553
And he makes no bones about it in his book.

32:30.874 --> 32:31.755
So, sure, there are cases.

32:32.115 --> 32:36.181
But I don't think that the basic nature of the book business has changed that much.

32:36.201 --> 32:38.184
I think human nature is the same.

32:38.224 --> 32:39.767
I think the nature of book selling is the same.

32:39.807 --> 32:42.451
I think the psychology of book selling is essentially the same.

32:42.471 --> 32:43.953
Psychology of collecting as well.

32:44.293 --> 32:45.816
And I think the psychology of collecting as well.

32:45.836 --> 32:46.056
Absolutely.

32:46.407 --> 32:51.814
I don't even know where it goes.

32:52.034 --> 32:53.937
Why should it change?

32:53.977 --> 32:55.859
Human nature stays the same.

32:55.959 --> 32:57.181
All this change is pricing.

32:57.421 --> 32:59.063
What's changing?

32:59.224 --> 33:00.045
Pace changes.

33:00.065 --> 33:00.886
Pace changes.

33:01.246 --> 33:03.930
General Harry can't give away today for instance.

33:03.990 --> 33:04.631
Pace changes.

33:04.891 --> 33:05.952
Prices change.

33:06.633 --> 33:09.096
The mechanics change and the fax machine has changed.

33:09.557 --> 33:10.959
Trading and collected enormously.

33:10.999 --> 33:12.240
So has the telephone.

33:12.481 --> 33:13.562
What you don't find anymore

33:13.778 --> 33:20.567
is the charming idea of Mr. Rosenbach taking a suitcase full of books and taking a train across the country to San Marino, California.

33:20.587 --> 33:21.028
That's right.

33:21.088 --> 33:23.852
Those stories are marvellous.

33:23.872 --> 33:29.439
And, you know, he gets invited to dinner, and he always sold something, and he knew just what to put in his suitcase.

33:29.479 --> 33:36.529
One of the final letters that Huntington wrote Rosenbach, which I'm having copied, is that you're certainly welcome to come and stay at the ranch

33:36.712 --> 33:39.755
But don't bring any books.

33:40.015 --> 33:42.317
I'm not trying anymore.

33:42.437 --> 33:45.040
That essentially is really the beginning.

33:45.740 --> 33:48.603
I think the style has changed.

33:48.623 --> 33:49.544
People aren't so elegant.

33:49.584 --> 33:50.865
People don't write so much anymore.

33:50.885 --> 33:52.287
You pick up the phone.

33:52.307 --> 33:58.252
You go through correspondence and you'd have four letters about the sale of a $20 book.

33:58.713 --> 34:01.135
Now you make one phone call to sell a $10,000 book.

34:01.475 --> 34:02.777
So those have changed.

34:02.797 --> 34:05.419
But the basic nature of it.

34:05.787 --> 34:14.039
And the Scheide case, for instance, I went to all of Rosenbach's correspondence with John Scheide, someone named Gutenberg, and then it ends.

34:15.040 --> 34:16.562
And I don't know what they paid for it.

34:16.702 --> 34:18.165
I bet.

34:18.565 --> 34:21.269
Well, what happened is I know exactly what happened.

34:21.349 --> 34:24.494
There was finally a Western Union telegram set, and it's there.

34:24.714 --> 34:26.697
I have to see you out in Titusville.

34:26.937 --> 34:29.421
So he went out, and it was done face to face.

34:29.841 --> 34:32.104
So the deal went down face to face.

34:32.345 --> 34:35.389
So the correspondence, which is wonderful, tracing the whole background,

34:35.588 --> 34:36.830
It doesn't have the last day.

34:37.250 --> 34:39.694
I mean, I would, you know, you want things to pursue.

34:40.695 --> 34:41.757
Yes, I would love it.

34:41.817 --> 34:48.687
You know, one of the questions last night was what effect does taxation have on collecting?

34:48.707 --> 34:50.530
Oh, it's changed the whole thing.

34:50.590 --> 34:55.297
The collector is now... But which piece of which collecting has taxation?

34:55.377 --> 34:59.663
Well, the private collector is now preeminent again in the not giving stuff to institutions.

34:59.823 --> 35:03.008
Institutions have really been hurt by it because you can't write off gifts.

35:03.249 --> 35:04.971
That's not...

35:05.305 --> 35:08.230
I don't know about taxation in terms of buying and selling if you sell a book.

35:09.612 --> 35:14.480
I'm not sure you want to put it in your book, but in a sense.

35:14.720 --> 35:16.864
It might have to do with investing.

35:16.884 --> 35:18.847
You have an underground economy.

35:18.867 --> 35:19.909
Books are being bought and sold.

35:20.470 --> 35:21.411
As investments.

35:21.431 --> 35:26.500
No, they're being bought and sold, and it's an undeclared form of investment.

35:26.820 --> 35:28.663
If I buy security, I've got to report it.

35:29.065 --> 35:31.928
You've got to report the purchase and the sale.

35:32.149 --> 35:41.259
But if I've got a thing going, if I'm a dealer and you're a collector, and you and I are sort of trading books back and forth, I mean, technically it's the same as trading securities, isn't it?

35:42.781 --> 35:44.824
But how many people do you think report those transactions?

35:44.844 --> 35:45.685
Trading and what?

35:45.705 --> 35:47.307
You mean trading in the... Trading enough.

35:47.367 --> 35:52.252
I've got three copies of Don Quicksit, so I'll trade you my two Quicksits for a da-da-da.

35:52.573 --> 35:55.096
You're either upgrading your collection or you're trading things.

35:55.336 --> 35:58.600
I bought something in London, and you're not only my dealer, but you're my friend.

35:59.221 --> 36:00.925
I mean, this goes on all the time.

36:00.966 --> 36:03.171
Well, Chef Louis Zatmari, you know him?

36:03.913 --> 36:07.442
He told me he did a lot of consulting stuff.

36:07.462 --> 36:08.846
And he got paid and booked.

36:09.187 --> 36:12.054
And he said, well, what I would do is tell him, he said, well, we want to give you some money.

36:12.074 --> 36:13.939
And I'd say, well, you know, I don't want any money, but

36:14.290 --> 36:19.656
If you go down the street in such and such a bookstore, there's a wonderfully tunable there.

36:19.756 --> 36:21.758
It probably costs $1,000 or something like that.

36:21.899 --> 36:22.419
It's a barter.

36:22.439 --> 36:25.763
He would have that thing delivered by messenger within 24 hours.

36:25.823 --> 36:26.724
It's a barter scheme.

36:26.764 --> 36:28.706
And that never got reported in his income tax.

36:28.726 --> 36:30.108
And he said that to me on the records.

36:30.128 --> 36:30.949
That's why I'm repeating.

36:31.209 --> 36:40.700
Well, I'm saying if you, not on the record, not on the record, but basically, I don't know if it really affects the market, but I think it's an interesting sidelight.

36:41.320 --> 36:41.581
It is.

36:41.761 --> 36:42.762
Which is interesting to me.

36:43.028 --> 36:52.097
You know, most people, most collectors who either buy and sell books or trade books aren't really doing it for the profit, and yet in the process, frequently do make a profit.

36:52.117 --> 36:54.339
A serious collector isn't it for the money, anyway.

36:54.359 --> 36:56.201
Well, it's a bad way to make money.

36:56.962 --> 36:57.062
Sure.

36:57.082 --> 36:58.443
Especially if you're buying from dealers.

36:59.384 --> 37:01.947
Because it's going to be very bad to recruit.

37:01.967 --> 37:02.087
Uh-uh.

37:02.107 --> 37:02.868
Go back to him no more.

37:02.888 --> 37:03.488
He did very well.

37:04.649 --> 37:05.450
Are you sure could he not?

37:05.470 --> 37:06.211
We don't know that.

37:06.972 --> 37:07.692
We're pretty sure.

37:07.712 --> 37:10.355
We don't know what they paid for a lot of these things.

37:10.375 --> 37:12.377
But talk about that.

37:12.813 --> 37:14.736
Considering the prices he made money.

37:15.016 --> 37:22.126
I'd be very interested to see what he paid Fleming for a lot of these things, because I knew off the record what he paid him for a lot of these things.

37:22.146 --> 37:24.129
No, but there's enough items that came up with that.

37:24.349 --> 37:28.395
Well, the Cervantes was expected to go for $250,000.

37:28.415 --> 37:30.137
It goes for $1.65 million.

37:30.157 --> 37:31.700
The Shakespeare's, he paid $165,000.

37:31.820 --> 37:33.342
Well, they got $2 million.

37:33.462 --> 37:35.625
All right, so there are two items right there.

37:35.946 --> 37:38.089
That will take care of the rest of the loan.

37:38.109 --> 37:40.091
That will take care of a lot of mistakes.

37:40.111 --> 37:41.233
Yeah, yeah.

37:42.074 --> 37:43.744
You've given me more time.

37:44.206 --> 37:45.172
Thank you very much.

37:45.313 --> 37:46.178
I'm available.

37:46.198 --> 37:47.747
It happens to be very busy.

